<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My induction cooktop isn't heating, is it broken?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Before assuming the cooktop is faulty, test cookware compatibility. Induction only works with ferromagnetic cookware, cast iron, magnetic stainless steel, and enameled steel. Copper, aluminum, glass, and non-magnetic stainless steel will not heat at all even on a perfectly working induction cooktop. Place a refrigerator magnet on the bottom of the pan, if it sticks firmly, the pan is compatible. A surprising number of 'my new induction cooktop is broken' service calls turn out to be cookware that was carried over from a gas or electric kitchen. If your cookware is confirmed magnetic and the cooktop still won't heat, then it's a genuine fault, most often the IGBT inverter module or the control board."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does the F error code on my induction cooktop mean?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "F-codes on induction cooktops are brand-specific and map to distinct fault categories. On Miele and Bosch, F0 typically indicates a touch control communication fault, F2 points to a temperature sensor, and F7 usually means main control board or power supply. Thermador and Wolf use similar but not identical codes. We decode the exact code for the specific model before touching any hardware, guessing based on a generic F-code chart often leads to replacing the wrong part. If you have an F-code displayed, have the model number ready when you call and we'll often know the likely cause before arrival."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which areas of Southern California do you cover for induction cooktop repair?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Same-day across Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties, Beverly Hills and Brentwood gas-to-induction conversions, Newport Coast and Irvine premium kitchens, Thousand Oaks and Westlake Village in Ventura, Rancho Cucamonga and Riverside in the Inland Empire. Eight service territories total. Wolf, Thermador, Miele, Gaggenau, Bosch, every premium induction brand running SoCal kitchens. BHGS Licensed #A49573."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Wolf, Thermador, and Miele induction cooktops?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, these are among our most frequent induction service calls, especially as electrification ordinances and the broader gas-to-induction conversion trend across SoCal (LA's new-construction gas restrictions, AQMD pressure on combustion appliances, and tax incentives for heat-pump and induction conversions across multiple jurisdictions) drive premium-brand induction volume. Wolf CT-series, Thermador Freedom and Masterpiece induction, and Miele KM-series are all serviceable with OEM parts. Lead time is something to flag: Miele and Gaggenau parts often ship from Germany and can take 5–10 business days; Wolf and Thermador domestic stock is usually faster. We give you the honest timeline before we order anything."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My induction cooktop shuts off during cooking, what's wrong?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Induction cooktops shutting off mid-use is almost always a thermal protection event, the internal electronics are overheating and the safety circuit is cutting power. The most common cause is a failed cooling fan. Induction generates significant heat inside the housing (the IGBTs run hot) and a small internal fan pulls air across the electronics. When the fan bearing seizes or the motor fails, the electronics hit their thermal limit within 5–15 minutes and the cooktop shuts down. Once everything cools, it will run again briefly, then shut off again. Fan replacement resolves this. Less commonly, a partially blocked ventilation slot (cabinet design issue) or a failing thermal sensor can produce the same symptom."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can induction coils be replaced individually?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "On most induction cooktops, yes, if the failure is on the inverter/IGBT side (which it usually is), we replace that module and restore the affected zone without touching the other zones. Some units have integrated coil-plus-inverter assemblies where the two parts come together as a single service component; on those, the unit cost is higher but the replacement is cleaner. A few higher-end models have individual zones that are effectively modular. We identify which configuration your specific model uses before quoting, the difference in part cost between a discrete IGBT module and a full coil-inverter assembly can be significant."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My induction cooktop glass cracked, should I repair or replace?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Depends on age, brand, and crack extent. Glass replacement on a 2-year-old Wolf, Thermador, or Miele induction is often worthwhile, the underlying electronics have most of their life left and the glass alone runs $550–$1400. On an older mid-range induction where the unit cost new is close to the glass replacement cost, replacement is usually the better call. We assess honestly. Until the glass is replaced, do not use the cooktop, induction with cracked glass allows moisture to reach the coils and electronics, and a spreading crack under a heavy pot can fail catastrophically."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When does it make sense to repair vs replace an induction cooktop?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under 5 years old: repair almost always wins, especially on premium brands. 5–10 years with a single inverter or fan failure on a Wolf, Thermador, Miele, or Gaggenau: repair, the rest of the unit has years of life. 10+ years with multiple failures, or a control-board failure on a mid-range unit where the board cost approaches replacement cost: we'll quote both and tell you directly which makes more financial sense. New induction cooktops run $1,400 (mid-range) to $5,000+ (premium European), plus install. Glass replacement on a 2-year-old premium unit with healthy electronics is almost always worthwhile."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does the 90-day warranty cover on induction cooktop repairs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every induction cooktop repair carries a 90-day warranty on parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. The warranty is given in writing before we leave. Note that warranty covers the specific repair performed, if a different component fails later, that's a separate service call."
      }
    }
  ]
