      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills · Wolf CT30IU 30" Induction</div>
        <h3>"Front left zone just stopped, the others still work"</h3>
        <p>Classic single-zone-dead presentation on a Wolf CT30IU that had been installed eight months earlier as part of a gas-to-induction conversion. Customer had previously had a Wolf gas range and swapped to induction to comply with the new building's electrification spec. Diagnostic pointed straight at the inverter module serving the front left zone, the IGBT stage had failed, likely a factory-defect early-life fault given the age. Coil tested healthy.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Sourced OEM Wolf inverter module (domestic stock, 48-hour turnaround). Replaced the inverter PCB, verified all four zones cycling through full power range including boost mode. Zone restored. Walked the customer through induction cookware compatibility while on-site, turned out one of their carry-over stainless pans was non-magnetic and never worked even when the cooktop was healthy.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Coast (OC) · Thermador CIT36XWB Masterpiece</div>
        <h3>"All zones work, but cooktop shuts off after 10 minutes at high heat"</h3>
        <p>Textbook cooling fan failure on a Newport Coast home Thermador. Customer ran the diagnostic herself before we arrived, she noticed the cooktop would work on simmer indefinitely but cut out reliably when she pushed two zones to high for more than 10 minutes. That specific pattern (thermal cutoff under high power) is the fan. Opened the underside, confirmed the internal cooling fan bearing had seized, the rotor wouldn't turn freely by hand.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced OEM Thermador fan motor assembly. Verified airflow with the replacement running, then ran a 20-minute load test with two zones on high and one at boost. No thermal shutdown. Explained the failure mode to the customer, she'd been running the cooktop hard for big coastal dinner parties, which accelerates fan wear on units without oversized ventilation.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura) · Miele KM 6879 Induction</div>
        <h3>"F7 error, the whole cooktop won't heat at all"</h3>
        <p>F7 on a Miele KM series is a main control board / power supply fault. Customer in Thousand Oaks recalled a heavy pasta boil-over a week earlier, water had gone down the sides of a large pot and she hadn't cleaned underneath aggressively. Opened the unit, confirmed moisture damage on the main control board with corrosion on several pads around the power input section. Coils, inverters, and fan all tested fine, the failure was isolated to the main board.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Main control board was not in domestic stock; Miele ships KM 6879 boards from Germany. Gave the customer a realistic 7–10 business day timeline, she preferred an honest long lead-time over a guess. Board arrived in eight days, installation took 45 minutes, F7 cleared, all four zones and touch panel functional. Customer appreciated being quoted the real timeline instead of "next week" and then extensions.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena · Bosch Benchmark NITP669SUC</div>
        <h3>"Dropped a cast iron skillet, cracked across two zones"</h3>
        <p>Two-year-old Bosch Benchmark with a crack running across two of the front zones after a cast iron skillet was dropped from overhead cabinet height. Electronics tested healthy, no error codes, coils and inverters all reading in spec with the crack bypassed. Real question was repair vs replace: unit was $2,100 new, glass replacement came to $850 installed, electronics had years of life remaining. We walked the customer through both paths honestly.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Customer chose repair, right call for a 2-year-old Benchmark with healthy internals. Ordered OEM Bosch glass assembly, replacement took about 2.5 hours onsite (careful removal of cracked panel, full coil and sensor reseat, new glass installed, all zones re-verified). Cooktop back to original condition. At replacement cost almost equal to a new mid-range unit, the decision was close, for a premium brand with healthy electronics, glass replacement is usually the right answer.</div>
